snippet.textDisplay:
Guys, listen to your informed audience. Relocate those batteries! Follow code. You need to meet ventilation, fire barrier, arc proof wiring methods and circuit protection regulations. These are not hypothetical risks. All that has to happen is the charger either fails to recognize the battery is fully charged or the current limit setting is wrongly adjusted resulting in the solar panels overcharging your batteries and producing a lot of hydrogen that will collect inside the cabin, mix with the oxygen in the air, creating a very combustive, explosive atmosphere. Why does it collect? You got the HVAC going and have closed the door and windows to stay cool. Hydrogen is odorless, colorless and deadly. You've assembled a system, experienced some learnings, got it working but you have not proven it's safe operations under all conditions including probable malfunction or maladjustment. You need multiple safeguards independent of the occupant's actions.

You don't want to make the leap from YouTube to Fox News! I am not being critical just honest. I am an electrical engineer in the energy sector and I've investigated too many fatal incidents and several battery bank explosions! Most common cause casual design practices.
